{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6d317a85-431b-4e5f-8dac-faaa01cb627f","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool**:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical setting that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required for tools.\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWould you like me to scaffold the project with these settings?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7258d1c7-0852-460f-8d3b-cfe21635358a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory doesn't exist yet. The user is asking what they need to configure, not asking me to do it. Let me give them guidance on what's needed to publish a C# MCP server as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org.","outputTokens":512,"requestId":"F3C5:BE897:1D59D43:21AE223:69F54EC0"},"id":"b7d74451-0bcf-409e-b7aa-746deaaa9077","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:09:29.338Z","parentId":"b0686a45-137a-4f3a-b962-7cd98eb9effb"}
